{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:16:49.829581+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have all the information needed. Here's the summary:\n\n---\n\n## Module Structure Summary\n\nThis is a **Spring Boot 4.0.0 (Java 25)** multi-module Gradle project organized into **five top-level module groups**, each responsible for a distinct architectural concern. The design philosophy (stated in the README) is: a *good-enough* structure for early-stage productivity, intended to evolve as the service grows.\n\n### 1. `core/` — Domain & Application Layer\n\nThis is the heart of the application. It contains two submodules:\n\n| Submodule | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| **`core:core-api`** | The **only executable module** (has `bootJar.enabled = true`). It hosts domain services, REST controllers, and Spring Boot framework configuration. It pulls in all other modules as dependencies (`core-enum`, `support:monitoring`, `support:logging`, `storage:db-core`, `clients:client-example`) and exposes the `spring-boot-starter-webmvc` web layer. |\n| **`core:core-enum`** | Contains **shared enumerations** used by `core-api` that also need to be exported to external consumers. It has no Spring-specific dependencies — it's a plain Java library. |\n\n### 2. `clients/` — External System Integration\n\nSubmodules here encapsulate outbound communication with third-party or external services.\n\n| Submodule | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| **`clients:client-example`** | A reference implementation showing how to integrate via **Spring Cloud OpenFeign** (with HC5 HTTP client and Micrometer metrics). Acts as a template for adding more client adapters (e.g., payment gateways, message brokers, etc.). |\n\n### 3. `storage/` — Persistence Layer\n\nSubmodules here handle data storage integrations.\n\n| Submodule | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| **`storage:db-core`** | Demonstrates database access using **Spring Data JPA** with a **MySQL** production driver and an **H2** in-memory driver for tests. Depends on `core:core-enum` for shared entity-related enumerations. |\n\n### 4. `support/` — Cross-Cutting Infrastructure\n\nSubmodules provide non-functional / operational capabilities.\n\n| Submodule | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| **`support:logging`** | Sets up **structured logging** via Spring Boot's OpenTelemetry starter (distributed tracing support) and **Sentry** error tracking (via `sentry-logback`). |\n| **`support:monitoring`** | Provides **observability** through Spring Boot Actuator and **Micrometer with a Prometheus registry** for metrics export. |\n\n### 5. `tests/` — Testing Utilities\n\nSubmodules here help with test authoring and documentation.\n\n| Submodule | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| **`tests:api-docs`** | A convenience module for writing **Spring REST Docs** tests. It brings in `spring-restdocs-mockmvc` so that `core-api`'s test suite can auto-generate AsciiDoc API documentation from MockMvc-based integration tests. |\n\n---\n\n### Dependency Flow (at a glance)\n\n```\ncore-api  (bootJar — the deployable artifact)\n  ├── core-enum\n  ├── clients/client-example\n  ├── storage/db-core  ──► core-enum\n  ├── support/logging\n  ├── support/monitoring\n  └── tests/api-docs   (testImplementation only)\n```\n\n`core-api` is the aggregator: it assembles all domain logic, infrastructure, and integrations into a single runnable Spring Boot application. Every other module is a **library** (`jar.enabled = true`, `bootJar.enabled = false`), reinforcing a clean separation of concerns.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 813, "prompt_tokens": 8693, "total_tokens": 9506, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 14, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 8448, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inf